&gt; My impression is that this tool reads a file entirely with the resulting line objects kept in memory

No. The use of memory is governed by how you choose to interact with your `CSVParser` object. 

The Javadoc for [`CSVParser`][1] addresses this issue explicitly, in its sections *Parsing record wise* versus *Parsing into memory*, with a caution:

&gt;Parsing into memory may consume a lot of system resources depending on the input. For example if you&#39;re parsing a 150MB file of CSV data the contents will be read completely into memory.

I took a quick glance at the source code, and indeed parsing record wise seems to be reading from its input source a chunk at a time, not all at once. But [see for yourself][2].

# Parsing record wise

In section *Parsing record wise*, it shows how to incrementally read one `CSVRecord` at a time by looping the [`Iterable`][3] that is `CSVParser`.

    CSVParser parser = CSVParser.parse(csvData, CSVFormat.RFC4180);
    for (CSVRecord csvRecord : parser) {
        ...
    }

# Parsing into memory

In contrast, the *Parsing into memory* section shows the use of [`CSVParser::getRecords`][4] to load all the `CSVRecord` objects into a `List` all at once, in memory. So obviously a very large input file could blow out memory on a constrained machine.

    Reader in = new StringReader(&quot;a;b\nc;d&quot;);
    CSVParser parser = new CSVParser(in, CSVFormat.EXCEL);
    List&lt;CSVRecord&gt; list = parser.getRecords();


